English <i>scearu</i> ‘boundary’ + <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’.","Americanized form of French   Charron  , a metonymic occupational name for a cartwright."],"variants":[{"name":"Scarrow","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire and Suffolk): perhaps ultimately a habitational name from Skirwith in Ingleton (Yorkshire), from Old Norse <i>skírr</i> ‘bright’ + <i>hofuth</i> ‘head, headland’. In the late 16th and 17th centuries the name appears as <i>Skarowe</i>, <i>Scaroe</i>, <i>Skerro</i>, and <i>Scarrou</i>; it presumably migrated to Cambridgeshire by the late 16th century, unless the Cambridgeshire name has a different, unexplained origin. Compare   Sharrow  ."]},{"name":"Sharrah","meanings":["English (East Yorkshire): variant of   Sharrow  . This form of the surname has now died out in Britain."]},{"name":"Charron","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Armand, Donat, Lucien, Marcel, Alphonse, Emile, Laurent, Normand, Renald, Yves, Adrien.","French: metonymic occupational name for a cartwright, from Old French <i>charron</i> ‘cart’ (from Latin <i>carro</i>, genitive <i>carronis</i>, a derivative of <i>carrum</i> ‘cart’). Compare   Charon  ,   Sharon  ,   Sharron  , and   Sharrow  .","History: Pierre Charron <i>dit</i> Ducharme from Meaux in Seine-et-Marne, France, married Catherine Pillard in Montreal, QC, in 1665; see also   Ducharme  . Jean Charron <i>dit</i> Laferrière from Saintes in Charente-Maritime, France, married Anne d'Anneville in Quebec City, QC, in 1669; see also   Laferriere  . Charles Charron <i>dit</i> Larose and Cabanac from Chartres in Eure-et-Loir, France, married Élisabeth Poupard in Montreal, QC, in 1713."]}]},{"name":"Samson","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."],"variants":[{"name":"Sampson","meanings":["Biblical name (Hebrew <i>Shimshon</i>, probably derived from <i>shemesh</i> ‘sun’), borne by a Jewish champion and judge famous for his prodigious strength. He was betrayed by his mistress, Delilah, and enslaved and blinded by the Philistines; nevertheless, he was able to bring the pillars of the temple of the Philistines crashing down in a final suicidal act of strength (Judges 13–16). This famous story provided the theme for  Milton's  poetic drama Samson Agonistes (  1671 ), which is modelled on ancient Greek tragedy. In the Middle Ages the popularity of the given name was increased in Celtic areas by the fame of a 6th-century Celtic saint who bore it, probably as a classicized form of some ancient Celtic name. He was a Welsh monk who did missionary work in Cornwall and afterwards established a monastery at Dol in Brittany."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":47,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":56,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705205,"age":67,"year":"1569","julianDay":2294126,"title":"State Lottery","description":"A State Lottery was recorded in 1569. The tickets were sold at St. Paul's Cathedral in London.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705206,"age":69,"year":"1571","julianDay":2294856,"title":"The Royal Exchange is Organized","description":"The Royal Exchange was organized in January 1571 by Sir Thomas Gresham. Gresham is known as the father of English banking.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705210,"age":98,"year":"1600","julianDay":2305448,"title":"The Honourable East India Company","description":"The Honourable East India Company, a British joint-stock company, was established in 1600 for trade in the Indian Ocean region. At its height, the British East India Company had a private army which was twice the size of the British Army, ruled large sections of India, and revenues in the millions.","url":"https://www.historic-uk.com/HistoryUK/HistoryofEngland/The-East-India-Company/","urlTitle":"Historic UK - The East India Company","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705212,"age":118,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Samson Sharrot was born in 1502, in Norfolk, England. He married Margaret Sharrott in 1524, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter. He died in Norfolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1502–":"1502–Surnud","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1532–1569":"1532–1569","1502–Male":"1502–Surnud","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"1502–":"1502–Kuollut","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1532–1569":"1532–1569","1502–Male":"1502–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","England":"Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Yorkshire, England"},"fr":{"1502–":"1502–Décédé","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1532–1569":"1532–1569","1502–Male":"1502–Décédé","1558":"1558","1569":"1569","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","1600":"1600","1532":"1532","1620":"1620","1575":"1575","1571":"1571","1549":"1549","1505":"1505","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","England":"Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Harewood, Yorkshire, England":"Harewood, Everwyck, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Samson Sharrot est né en 1502, à Norfolk, Angleterre. Il a épousé Margaret Sharrott en 1524, à Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille. Il est décédé à Norfolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni."},"de":{"1502–":"1502–Verstorben","1505–1575":"1505–1575","1532